Here's the context of the blog post

React Native developers often face the problem of adding native support for multiple operating systems, which takes time and effort. What if there was an open source project to handle In-App purchasing (IAP) dependencies across iOS, Google PlayStore, and Amazon Appstore for you? Hello react-native-iap!

I recently had this challenge while integrating Amazon IAP in a React Native app. After researching the top open source projects for purchasing, react-native-iap enabled IAP functionality without the complexity of operating system specific APIs — truly one (react native) package to rule them all! 🧙‍♂️✨

For this article, I am going to walk you through the project and then I’ll explain how I launched their sample with the Amazon IAP App Tester.

⬇️ The sample app
The first thing I did was clone the Github repository for react-native-iap as it contained all the working examples for Amazon Appstore, Google Play, and Apple Appstore.

git clone https://github.com/dooboolab/react-native-iap


🪝 The useIAP hook for all the stores
Exploring the sample I saw it uses their new useIAP hook that handles purchases for all the different stores. This was great as the useIAP hook allows you to access a number of operating system agnostic variables and functions allowing you to use the reuse the same logic across platforms.

Taking the example of scenario where a user is making a purchase of a subscription, I mapped how I could utilise the variables and functions:

Retrieve the available subscriptions
The first step would be to retrieve the available subscriptions and present them to a user. I can easily do this by checking I am connected and then calling the getSubscriptions function. This will automatically update the subscriptions variable with the subscriptions:
 const {connected, subscriptions, getSubscriptions} = useIAP();

 useEffect(() => {
    if (connected) {
      getSubscriptions({skus: [
        'com.amazon.sample.iap.subscription.mymagazine.month',
        'com.amazon.sample.iap.subscription.mymagazine.quarter',
      ]});
    }
  }, [getSubscriptions]);
Handle the purchase request
Next to handle a purchase request e.g. when a purchaseSubscription button is pressed, I can make my call of requestSubscription:
 requestSubscription = async (sku: Sku) => {
    try {
      await requestSubscription({sku});
    } catch (error) {
      //Handle error
    }
  };
Handle errors
Next, I can wrap my currentPurchaseError in a useEffect and listen to check if any error occurred and then handle it accordingly:
  const {currentPurchaseError} = useIAP();

  useEffect(() => {
    ... 
  }, [currentPurchaseError]);
Check current purchase
Finally, asynchronously, I can create a function to check the status and execute finishTransaction:
  const {currentPurchase, finishTransaction} = useIAP();

  useEffect(() => {
    const checkCurrentPurchase = async () => {
      try {
        if (currentPurchase?.productId) {
          await finishTransaction({
            purchase: currentPurchase,
            isConsumable: true,
          });
        }
      } catch (error) {
          //Handle error
      }
    };

    checkCurrentPurchase();
  }, [currentPurchase, finishTransaction]);
🧪 Test with the Amazon App Tester
The sample looked great so it was now time to unit test IAP functionality by simulating a production environment with the Amazon IAP App Tester in three steps.

Step 1: Download the App Tester
If you haven't already got it, you can download App Tester from the Amazon Appstore, onto the same Android device as your app. The App Tester simulates the production environment and you configure it with IAP items.

Step 2: Create the amazon.sdktester.json
The example app already contains the JSON file with the IAP Items used in the demo and you can find it in IAPExample/android/app/amazon.sdktester.json

However, you could also create your own IAP items here. Once you have created your in-app items, you can download a JSON-formatted data file containing all of the data for your items like the one above.

Step 3: Push the amazon.sdktester.json file to your device
Next, if you haven't already, connect your Amazon device with your developer environment using the Android Debug Bridge (adb). This is to enable you to copy the JSON file to the /sdcard/ folder on your device file system by running the following command line:
$ adb push [_Your_JSON_File_Folder_]/amazon.sdktester.json /sdcard/amazon.sdktester.json

Note: If your device is running an Android OS version older than 4.0, copy the file to /mnt/sdcard/.

Once that is set-up you will see the In-App items on the App Tester.

Finally, running the Amazon version of the example app with the command yarn android:amazon you can test purchases using Amazon IAP:

Big kudos to lead maintainer @andresesfm and the all the contributions from community developers for react-native-iap! Consider showing your support to their open source project on OpenCollective. I’ll definitely be using their package to implement Amazon IAP in my React Native App!

Yes, the Square Catalog API does support custom attributes.

You can use the "custom\_attribute\_values" field to set custom attribute values for a catalog object, such as an item variation or modifier option. You can define up to 60 custom attribute names and values for each object.

Here's an example of how you can create an item variation with a custom attribute using the Square Catalog API:


```json
{
 "type": "ITEM\_VARIATION",
 "id": "12345",
 "item\_id": "67890",
 "name": "Small",
 "price\_money": {
 "amount": 100,
 "currency\_code": "USD"
 },
 "custom\_attribute\_values": [
 {
 "custom\_attribute\_definition\_id": "custom\_attribute\_id",
 "string\_value": "Red"
 }
 ]
}
```
In this example, the custom attribute name is "custom\_attribute\_id" and the value is "Red". You would need to define the custom attribute name beforehand using the Square API.

You can find more information about how to use custom attributes in the Square Catalog API documentation: <https://developer.squareup.com/docs/catalog-api/overview/custom-attributes>

One mechanism to select an escrow in a decentralized way is by using a puzzle that nodes in the network can solve to compete for the role of being the escrow. Here's a possible mechanism with steps:

1. Define the puzzle: The puzzle should be difficult enough that only a few nodes in the network can solve it, but not so difficult that it's impossible to solve. The puzzle should also be fair, meaning that any node in the network should be able to solve it if they have the necessary resources and computing power. A possible puzzle could be a cryptographic hash function that takes a specific input and produces a specific output.
2. Publish the puzzle: The puzzle should be published to the network, along with the requirements for solving it and the rewards for solving it.
3. Nodes try to solve the puzzle: Nodes in the network will compete to solve the puzzle and claim the rewards. Each node will try to solve the puzzle using their own computing power and resources. Once a node solves the puzzle, they will notify the network that they have solved it and provide the solution.
4. Verify the solution: Once a node claims to have solved the puzzle, other nodes in the network will verify the solution to ensure that it's correct. If the solution is correct, the node that solved the puzzle will be selected as the escrow.
5. Escrow performs the duties: Once the escrow is selected, they will perform the duties that are required of them, such as holding funds in escrow, mediating disputes, and releasing funds to the appropriate party.

Here's some pseudocode that shows how this mechanism could work:


```java
// Define the puzzle
puzzle_input = "some input"
puzzle_output = "some output"
puzzle_difficulty = 1000

// Publish the puzzle
publish_puzzle(puzzle_input, puzzle_output, puzzle_difficulty)

// Nodes try to solve the puzzle
while true:
 solution = solve_puzzle(puzzle_input, puzzle_difficulty)
 if solution:
 // Verify the solution
 if verify\_solution(solution, puzzle\_input, puzzle\_output):
 // Escrow selected
 select_escrow(node_id)
 break
```
In this pseudocode, `solve_puzzle()` is a function that takes the puzzle input and difficulty as inputs and tries to find a solution to the puzzle. `verify_solution()` is a function that checks whether a solution is correct by checking if the output of the puzzle function matches the puzzle output. `select_escrow()` is a function that selects the node that solved the puzzle as the escrow.

Here's some pseudocode that shows how node A can initiate the steps to start sending money through the escrow node:


```kotlin
// Set up connection with escrow node
escrow_node = select_random_node()
connect_to_node(escrow_node)

// Generate a transaction
tx_input = "input address"
tx_output = "output address"
tx_amount = 100
tx_fee = 10
transaction = generate_transaction(tx_input, tx_output, tx_amount, tx_fee)

// Send transaction to escrow node
send_transaction_to_node(transaction, escrow_node)

// Wait for confirmation from escrow node
while true:
 confirmation = get_confirmation_from_node(escrow_node)
 if confirmation:
 break

// Send payment to escrow node
send_payment_to_escrow_node(tx_amount + tx_fee, escrow_node)

// Wait for confirmation from escrow node
while true:
 confirmation = get_confirmation_from_node(escrow_node)
 if confirmation:
 break

// Wait for confirmation of payment from escrow node
while true:
 payment_confirmation = get_payment_confirmation_from_escrow_node()
 if payment_confirmation:
 // Payment complete
 break
```
In this pseudocode, `select_random_node()` is a function that selects a random node from the network to be the escrow. `connect_to_node(node)` is a function that sets up a connection with a given node. `generate_transaction(input, output, amount, fee)` is a function that generates a transaction with a given input, output, amount, and fee. `send_transaction_to_node(transaction, node)` is a function that sends a transaction to a given node. `get_confirmation_from_node(node)` is a function that waits for a confirmation of the transaction from the escrow node. `send_payment_to_escrow_node(amount, node)` is a function that sends a payment to the escrow node for the transaction amount and fee. `get_payment_confirmation_from_escrow_node()` is a function that waits for a confirmation of the payment from the escrow node.

Note that this pseudocode is just a rough outline and would need to be adapted to the specific implementation of the bitcoin network and the escrow mechanism being used. Additionally, the implementation would need to consider security measures such as encrypting communication, protecting private keys, and preventing double-spending attacks.

Here's some pseudocode that shows how a node can validate a transaction by checking all the way back for the presence of a specific address or amount:


```kotlin
function validate_transaction(transaction):
 // Check if transaction is valid
 if not is_valid(transaction):
 return False

 // Check if transaction input is unspent
 if not is_unspent(transaction.input):
 return False

 // Check if transaction output amount is valid
 if not is_valid_output_amount(transaction.output):
 return False

 // Check if transaction input address is valid
 if not is_valid_address(transaction.input.address):
 return False

 // Check if transaction output address is valid
 if not is_valid_address(transaction.output.address):
 return False

 // Check if transaction input amount is greater than or equal to the output amount
 if not is_input_amount_sufficient(transaction.input.amount, transaction.output.amount):
 return False

 // Check all the way back to the genesis block to see if the input address has sufficient funds
 current_block = get_latest_block()
 while current_block is not None:
 for tx in current_block.transactions:
 if tx.output.address == transaction.input.address:
 if tx.output.amount >= transaction.input.amount:
 return True
 current_block = get_previous_block(current_block)

 // If the input address doesn't have sufficient funds, the transaction is invalid
 return False
```
In this pseudocode, `is_valid(transaction)` is a function that checks whether the transaction is valid according to the Bitcoin protocol rules. `is_unspent(transaction.input)` is a function that checks whether the transaction input has not been spent already. `is_valid_output_amount(transaction.output)` is a function that checks whether the output amount is a valid amount (i.e., not negative or greater than the maximum allowed value). `is_valid_address(address)` is a function that checks whether the given address is a valid Bitcoin address. `is_input_amount_sufficient(input_amount, output_amount)` is a function that checks whether the input amount is greater than or equal to the output amount. `get_latest_block()` is a function that returns the latest block in the blockchain. `get_previous_block(block)` is a function that returns the previous block in the blockchain.

Note that this pseudocode is just a rough outline and would need to be adapted to the specific implementation of the Bitcoin network being used. Additionally, the implementation would need to consider security measures such as preventing double-spending attacks and protecting against fraudulent transactions.

