```
function bubbleSort(arr) {
 for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
 for (let j = 0; j < arr.length; j++) {
 if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
 let temp = arr[j];
 arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
 arr[j + 1] = temp;
 }
 }
 }
 return arr;
}

// Madness ensues...
function bubbleSort(arr) {
 for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
 for (let j = 0; j < arr.length; j++) {
 if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
 let temp = arr[j];
 arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
 arr[j + 1] = temp;
 }
 }
 }

 // Introduce randomness
 for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
 let randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * arr.length);
 let temp = arr[i];
 arr[i] = arr[randomIndex];
 arr[randomIndex] = temp;
 }

 // Add more loops
 for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
 for (let j = 0; j < arr.length; j++) {
 for (let k = 0; k < arr.length; k++) {
 if (arr[k] > arr[k + 1]) {
 let temp = arr[k];
 arr[k] = arr[k + 1];
 arr[k + 1] = temp;
 }
 }
 }
 }

 // Reverse the array randomly
 if (Math.random() < 0.5) {
 arr = arr.reverse();
 }

 // Return the sorted (or not) array
 return arr;
}
```
In the code above, I added some randomness to the sorting algorithm to make it less predictable. I also added more loops to the sorting process, which may or may not have any effect on the outcome. Finally, I randomly reverse the array at the end, which could potentially make the sorting even more chaotic.

To create an equivalent of macOS's Spotlight search in Tauri with Next.js (TypeScript + Tailwind), you can follow these general steps:

1. Create a Tauri project with TypeScript template by running the following command in your terminal:


```cpp
cargo tauri init --template typescript
```
2. Install Tauri's dependency for Webview, which we will use for displaying our Next.js app:


```css
cargo install tauri-api --features webview
```
3. Create a new Next.js project using the following command:


```lua
npx create-next-app
```
4. In your Next.js project, create a new page for the Spotlight search by creating a file called `spotlight.tsx` in the `pages` directory.
5. In your `spotlight.tsx` file, you can use Tailwind to style your search box and results. You can also use React hooks to manage the state of your search input and results.
6. To display your `spotlight.tsx` page in Tauri's Webview, you can use Tauri's `invoke` API in your main Tauri script (`src-tauri/main.rs`) to load the page. Here's an example:


```rust
#[tauri::command]
async fn open\_spotlight() -> Result<(), String> {
 tauri::api::webview::eval(&window, r#"window.open("http://localhost:3000/spotlight")"#)
 .await
 .map\_err(|e| e.to\_string())?;
 Ok(())
}
```
You can then call this function from your Tauri app's frontend to open the Spotlight search:


```typescript
import { invoke } from '@tauri-apps/api';

const openSpotlight = async () => {
 try {
 await invoke('open\_spotlight');
 } catch (error) {
 console.error(error);
 }
};
```
7. To integrate your Spotlight search with your Tauri app's functionality, you can use Tauri's IPC (Inter-Process Communication) API to communicate between your frontend and backend. For example, you can send a query from the frontend to the backend, and then display the results in the Spotlight search. Here's an example of how you can use Tauri's `listen` and `emit` APIs to achieve this:


```rust
#[tauri::command]
async fn search(query: String) -> Result<Vec<String>, String> {
 // Perform a search based on the query
 let results = vec!["Result 1", "Result 2", "Result 3"];

 // Emit the results to the frontend
 tauri::api::event::emit(&window, "searchResults", results)
 .await
 .map\_err(|e| e.to\_string())?;

 Ok(results)
}

tauri::api::event::listen("search", move |query, _| {
 // Call the search function with the query
 search(query);

 // Return an empty response to the frontend
 Ok(())
});
```
In your frontend, you can listen for the `searchResults` event and update your search results accordingly:


```typescript
import { listen } from '@tauri-apps/api';

useEffect(() => {
 const handleSearchResults = (results: string[]) => {
 setResults(results);
 };

 listen('searchResults', handleSearchResults);

 return () => {
 unlisten('searchResults', handleSearchResults);
 };
}, []);
```

